1315":"about 1315","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1282":"1282","1381":"1381","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Copton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Nottinghamshire): habitational name from any of various places called Colton in England. Examples in Norfolk, Staffordshire, and North Yorkshire are from the Old English personal name <i>Cola</i> (or the cognate Old Norse <i>Koli</i>; see   Cole   2) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The place so named in Somerset has as its first element the Old English personal name <i>Cūla</i> (of uncertain origin). The one in Cumbria has a river name apparently derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘hazel’. This English name is also common in Ireland; it was the name of a bishop of Derry in 1397. There seems also to have been confusion with   Culliton  .","Scottish and Irish (Monaghan): shortened and altered form of Gaelic <b>Mac Haldan</b>, ‘son of <i>Haldan</i>’, see   Haldane  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Culton","meanings":["Scottish (Kirkcudbrightshire): variant of   Colton   or   Culliton  ."]},{"name":"Cole","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."]},{"name":"Colten","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Colton  ."]},{"name":"Coulton","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Colton  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Copton was born in 1285, in Ipswich, Suffolk, England, his father, De Cropton, was 4 and his mother, Anwett Weyland, was 4. He married Mrs. Copton about 1315, in Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1319, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1285–1319":"1285–1319","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1317–1381":"1317–1381","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1282–1327":"1282–1327","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","about 1315":"umbes 1315","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1282":"1282","1381":"1381","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fi":{"1285–1319":"1285–1319","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","1317–1381":"1317–1381","1282–Male":"1282–Kuollut","1282–1327":"1282–1327","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","about 1315":"noin 1315","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1282":"1282","1381":"1381","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","London, England":"London, England"},"fr":{"1285–1319":"1285–1319","1295–Female":"1295–Décédée","1317–1381":"1317–1381","1282–Male":"1282–Décédé","1282–1327":"1282–1327","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","about 1315":"environ 1315","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1282":"1282","1381":"1381","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, Angleterre","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre","London, England":"Londres, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque John de Copton est né en 1285, à Ipswich, Suffolk, Angleterre, son père, De Cropton, avait 4 ans et sa mère, Anwett Weyland, avait 4 ans. Il a épousé Mrs. Copton environ 1315, à Suffolk, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé en 1319, à Suffolk, Angleterre, à l’âge de 34 ans."},"de